\f1\i\b\fs28 \cf0 ### Brief History of \'93mental illness\'94
\f0\i0\b0\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sb240\sa120\partightenfactor0

\f2 \cf0 \
What makes a certain condition a \'91mental\'92 condition or a 'medical' or \'92neurological\'92 condition?  Suppose you are a family doctor, and a patient presents with an unwelcome and unwanted problem---a twitch, perhaps. Do you call a psychiatrist or a neurologist? How do you know?
\f0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sb240\sa120\partightenfactor0

\f3 \cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa120\partightenfactor0
\cf0 While behaviors associated with mental illness---hallucinations, catatonic states, mania, etc.---have been known since ancient times, psychiatry dates its regularization as a scientific discipline to the work of the French physician Phillipe Pinel. His
\f4\i  *Trait\'e9 m\'e9dico-philosophique sur l'ali\'e9nation mentale; ou la manie*
\f3\i0  stands as the first attempt at a scientific classification of mental illness. The book, translated as
\f4\i  *Treatise on Insanity*
\f3\i0  in 1806 by D.D. Davis, is excerpted in Appendix 
\f5\b `\\fullref\{app: pinel\}`\{=latex\}
\f3\b0 .  
\f0 \

\f3 \
Pinel was an intellectual disciple of \'c9tienne Bonnot de Condillac, who in turn, was a disciple of John {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "scrivcmt://3C331A63-E57A-4032-9CF4-36ACE9DB924B"}}{\fldrslt Locke.}} Locke is most well known as the intellectual progenitor of the American Constitution, but his views on the nature of mind and the empirical basis of knowledge held sway over much of the Western intellectual world in the first half of the 19\super th\nosupersub  century.  Locke's influence on Condillac and hence Pinel was two-fold: first, he held that all our ideas originate in sensation and reflection. Second, and as importantly, Locke followed Francis Bacon in teaching that all knowledge must be based on careful, systematic observation.
\f0 \

\f3 \
For the empiricists, it follows that insanity, which is a severe form of our ideas 'leading us astray', is explained by a incorrect connection and association of ideas. The mechanism is simple: some of our ideas have a natural affinity or connection with one another. Others are held together by mere custom or habit. Cases of insanity are cases where habitual associations become so disorganized they begin to effect the 'natural' associations. This misassociation can become so extreme that it can \'93set us awry in our actions, as well moral as natural, passions, reasonings, and notions themselves\'94 [Bk 2, Ch 33, p9. Pg. 531][#Locke:1959wj]. To this day, we use metaphors like 'lost his senses' to describe someone with mental illness; and we describe poorly chosen actions as 'not very sensible.'
\f0 \

\f3 \
This is simply the theoretical basis for understanding insanity in the broadest possible terms.  To truly understand how mental disorder is defined and classified, we must consider how the mentally ill have been treated.
\f0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa120\partightenfactor0

\f3 \cf0 #### Foundations
\f0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sb240\sa120\partightenfactor0

\f6\b\fs28 \cf0 ##### Foundation in Empiricism: Phillipe Pinel
\f0\b0\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa120\partightenfactor0

\f3 \cf0 \
Phillipe Pinel (1745-1826) revolutionized the treatment of the insane. When, in 1792, he was appointed a physician at the main asylum in Paris---the Bic\'eatre hospital---the situation was dire. According to a biographer in 1846:
\f0 \

\f3 \
\pard\pardeftab720\li283\partightenfactor0
\cf0 > The buildings were unfit for habitation. In them were congregated men crouching together in the mud, in stone cells, narrow, cold, damp, destitute of air and light, and merely furnished with a straw bed, seldom renewed, and soon becoming foul and offensive; wretched dens, in which one would hesitate to place the meanest animal. The insane, who were immured in these filthy holes, were at the mercy of their attendants, and these persons were malefactors released from prison. The wretched patients were loaded with chains and manacled like convicts. Thus given up defenseless to the wickedness of their guardians, they were the sports of an insulting mockery, or of a brutality all the more blind that it was gratuitous. [p. 194-195][#Marx:1847vc]
\f0 \

\f3 \
\pard\pardeftab720\li283\fi-283\partightenfactor0
\cf0 Upon his arrival, Pinel immediately began advocating pity, respect, and compassion for the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "scrivcmt://7A7FFC94-0C0C-4A51-9F42-6686685D2B9C"}}{\fldrslt patients,}} not only for humanitarian reasons, but also in order to allow the Baconian method of careful observation. Given the terrible conditions at the Bic\'eatre, Pines argued, one would never be able to determine if the behavior of the patients was the result of some underlying condition, or the condition of the Hospital itself. Bic\'eatre's chief physician, Pussin, was sympathetic to Pinel's techniques, and began a pilot study of unchaining the patients.
\f0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f3 \cf0 \
\
Two years later, Pinel was appointed  chief physician of the Hospice de la Salp\'eatri\'e8re---Paris' parallel institution for women. There, the women were kept chained, often naked, in subterranean cells; subjected to the terrors of abusive guards and hungry rats. Pinel immediate banned the use of metal chains as restraints, allowed the women clothing, and established something resembling human {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "scrivcmt://7FECA261-7B48-470E-A91E-5A9C4DCDD80E"}}{\fldrslt civility.}} This act was mythologized during the French Revolution as part of the overthrow of the aristocratic order, and has been duly commemorated in {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "scrivcmt://8C87EF07-8E1C-4A6B-8A54-AD082F798149"}}{\fldrslt Art.}}
\f0 \

\f3 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa120\partightenfactor0
\cf0 Pinel's revolutionary kindness is not just a story of a sympathetic humanitarian.  Pinel's goal was to systematical classify mental illness in the Baconian manner.  The conditions of confinement found in the Bic\'eatre and the Salp\'eatri\'e8re compounded the patients' mental illness, and confounded his attempts at observation. In these conditions, one could not determine if the regularity of symptoms found in the population resulted from the illness or the \'91treatment.\'92 By providing the patients respect and dignity, he believed he could observe their mental illness in a more untainted form.
\f0 \

\f3 \
In general, Pinel followed Locke and Condillac in holding that insanity was 'derangement of the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "scrivcmt://A33ED385-FF53-4CEC-A511-EA76E8B98C64"}}{\fldrslt understanding\'92}}, yet extended the view to cover cases where memory, understanding and judgment were perfectly sound, and still the patient was maniacal. \
\
Pinel thus abandoned any formal all-encompassing theoretical explanation of insanity
\f4\i  per se
\f3\i0 , especially that which originated in Ancient Greek thought. The Greeks, he reasoned, were wrong about how the human brain functions, as we now understood. And as their system was based on their mistaken physiology, it is unreliable. \
\
Instead, Pinel explicitly bases his system on \'93the numerous and important facts which have been discovered and detailed by modern pneumatologists\'94 [p. 135][#Pinel:1806ws] \
