\f3 \cf0 \
#### Early Neurology\

\f0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sb240\sa120\partightenfactor0

\f2\fs28 \cf0 Western medicine understood that the nervous system used, or conducted, electricity from the Galvani\'92s famous frog-leg experiments of 1780. There were, as one might expect, different interpretation of the relationship between nerves and electricity---Galvani believed electricity was the \'91vital force\'92 contained in living {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "scrivcmt://5F1E0393-990C-4587-862D-3F83C4912863"}}{\fldrslt things}}. Galvani\'92s colleague Volta, who went on to lend his name to the \'91Volt\'92, argued that the frog leg reacted to electricity, but did not contain it.\
The precise relationship between nerves and electricity, as well as the relationship between the nervous system an our psychology, was not nailed down for a long time. But that didn\'92t stop researchers in this era from speculating wildly. One of the most famous, whose theories about psychology are enshrined in our language in terms as frequent as \'91nervous\'92, is George Beard.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sb240\sa120\partightenfactor0

\f6\b \cf0 \
#####  American Nervousness --- George Beard
\f0\b0\fs24 \

\f6\b\fs28 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa120\partightenfactor0

